# Functions to be used
def remove_urls(text):
    new_text = ' '.join(re.sub("(@[A-Za-z0-9]+)|([^0-9A-Za-z \t])|(\w+:\/\/\S+)"," ",text).split())
    return new_text

# Make all text lowercase
def text_lowercase(text): 
    return text.lower()

# Remove numbers
def remove_numbers(text): 
    result = re.sub(r'\d+', '', text) 
    return result

# Remove punctuation
def remove_punctuation(text): 
    translator = str.maketrans('', '', string.punctuation)
    return text.translate(translator)

# Function for all pre-processing steps
def preprocessing(text):
    text = text_lowercase(text)
    text = remove_urls(text)
    text = remove_numbers(text)
    text = remove_punctuation(text)
    return text

# Pre-processing the text body column
pp_text = []
for text_data in reviews['text']:
  # check if string
  if isinstance(text_data, str):
    pp_text_data = preprocessing(text_data)
    pp_text.append(pp_text_data)
   # if not string
  else:
    pp_text.append(np.NaN)
In [7]:
# Add pre-processed column to dataset
reviews['pp_text'] = pp_text

Logistic Regression with TfidVectorizer¶

In the final part of this project, we need to do the splitting of the data again, as we have made necessary modifications to the data for explainability, and we are using a different vectorizer than the one we have used in the models and the optimization.

In [12]:
# Let's do the data splitting again but in this case for a different logistic regression with modifications needed 
# in the data for explainability.
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size = 0.25, random_state = 0)
In [13]:
tf = TfidfVectorizer(strip_accents = 'ascii', stop_words = 'english')
In [14]:
# Transform and fit the training set with vectoriser
X_train_tf = tf.fit_transform(X_train)
# Transform the test set with vectoriser
X_test_tf = tf.transform(X_test)
In [15]:
# Create logistic regression model with l2 penalty for predictions.
LR = LogisticRegression(random_state=0, penalty='l2')
# Train model on  vectorised training data
model = LR.fit(X_train_tf, y_train)
# Evaluate model performance on the test set
pred = model.predict(X_test_tf)
In [16]:
print('Evaluation of the model:')
print(f'\nF2 Score: {fbeta_score(y_test, pred, beta = 2, average = "macro")}\n')
print(f'R2 Score: {r2_score(y_test, pred)}\n')
print('Accuracy of the model: {}\n'.format(accuracy_score(y_test, pred)))
print('Classification report: \n{}\n'.format(classification_report(y_test, pred)))

Conclusions

  • Using the Linear Regression model with a penalty L2 (Ridge), give us an F2 Score result of 93%, wich means that our model is very good at predicting the classes we are interested in, as it has high accuracy and high sensitivity. The model is very good at both detecting true positives and minimizing false negatives.

  • With this model, the result is that we obtain a recall of 99%, which indicates that the model identifies as positive the reviews in 99% of the cases, while the negative ones in 0.0077%, it is evident that it has a higher accuracy in the positive class (5.0).

  • The accuracy is quite high for both positive (97%) and negative reviews (96%), because it is quite accurate in classifying positives and negatives.

SHAP Explainability¶

In this case, we have chosen to use the SHAP model rather than LIME for explainability. SHAP offers us greater rigor and stability in our interpretability, although if time were a determining factor in our project, perhaps the LIME model would be a better choice.

In [18]:
import shap
shap.initjs()
In [19]:
# Sampling data from the training and test set to reduce time-taken
X_train_sample = shap.sample(X_train_tf, 200)
X_test_sample = shap.sample(X_test_tf, 40)

# Creating the KernelExplainer using the logistic regression model and training sample
SHAP_explainer = shap.KernelExplainer(model.predict, X_train_sample)
# calculating the shap values of the test sample using the explainer 
shap_vals = SHAP_explainer.shap_values(X_test_sample)

# Converting the test samples to a dataframe 
# this is necessary for non-tabular data in order for the visualisations 
# to include feature value
colour_test = pd.DataFrame(X_test_sample.todense())

Using 200 background data samples could cause slower run times. Consider using shap.sample(data, K) or shap.kmeans(data, K) to summarize the background as K samples.

  0%|          | 0/40 [00:00<?, ?it/s]

Global Explainability¶

In [20]:
# Plotting the global explainability
shap.summary_plot(shap_vals, colour_test, feature_names = tf.get_feature_names_out())

Insights

  • This graph shows the top 20 features in terms of their importance for predictions. The SHAP value on the x-axis shows whether the feature had a higher or lower prediction probability. Each dot represents a different test observation and the color of the dot is the importance of that feature for that particular prediction.

  • As expected, many good reviews such as great, beast, excelent, amazing, and more are present in the top 20 feature set due to the fact that good ratings have a higher weight relative to negative ratings in this dataset.
